<font color="#FF0000">HOW TO HONOUR</font><br>
<tt>Sat Feb 22  5:01:30 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
My eleven year old daughter gave up her birthday party, presents, a trip to Honolulu, something she had wanted to do for years, in exchange for me giving up smoking. On her own and out of the blue, she came up with this offer. This is my third night. This is my 4th attempt with the &quot;patch&quot;, maybe my twentieth time altogether. Been smoking since I was 13. Worst side effect of the patch, very vivid dreams. In color, very detailed and disturbing dreams. So here I suck on a unlit Tiparillo, plastic tip cigar and starlight mints, afraid to go to sleep. Don't care for the dreams.<br><br>
Does any vet remember how they remembered their fallen comrades BEFORE the Wall? For me, it was a very private, internal affair, as I'm sure it was with many others. I didn't talk about the war with anyone, hence, didn't talk of the dead. In 1973, for a class assignment, went to a synagogue for Yom Kippur. A woman sat by me.  She had the tatoo on her arm. She was alone. She was the only Holocaust survivor I had ever met up to then and since. I didn't say a word to her. We were informed by the rabbi of the new war between Irael and Syria and Egypt that very day. It must have been that day that I decided to know more about the Holocaust. I figured, also, that, since 'Nam was never going to have any monuments, no memorials, that I was going to adopt the Holocaust Memorials throughout Europe for &quot;my&quot; own guys. I fantasized that, one day, I would tour Europe on a quest, visit the death camps of Auschwitz, Dachau, Chelmno, Treblinka, Sorbibor, Mauthausen, Belzec, Ravensbruck, Majdanek, Birkenau, Buchenwald, Bergen-Belsen and honour those that Died there, Jews and non-Jews, and honour those that died in 'Nam also. Never did do it. Never visited the Wall, either.<br><br>
As a boy, because of a paper route, I met a first generation Japanese man. He had lost his two sons in the European Campaign of WWII, and his wife and baby in a relocation camp in the U.S.. Because of him, I learned all I could about the 442nd and what the war cost the American-Japanese.<br><br>
I already told the story of Mr. Quan and his story of war and death.<br><br>
In seeking information about what happened to a village in Cambodian that we had come across during the war, I began a process of learning what happened in that country and what it had cost them in terms of the human tragedy.<br><br>
I have no awards left.  The Holocaust survivor, eventually got one of them.  Mr. Quan got another.  My Combat Medic Badge went to a psychologist who worked with physically and sexually abused kids. She eventually &quot;offed&quot; herself. The toll of her work was high. The awards all went. The only regret I have is that there are none left for my daughter, otherwise, I have never been sorry about giving them away.<br><br>
I probably will never see the Wall, or any other memorial, for that fact.  So how can I honour those from 'Nam and all the other ghosts I have come across and accumulated?<br><br>
Only by never forgetting. And by learning. And by passing what I have learned to others.  If it will only be my daughter, it is one more than there would have been otherwise.
